<h1>TOMOYO Linux 1.8.x : Documentation</h1>
<table border="0" summary="What is TOMOYO Linux?">
<tr><td><img src="../tomoyo.png" alt="tomoyo.png" width="115" height="150"></td><td>TOMOYO Linux is a security module which focuses on the behavior of a system. Every process is created to achieve a purpose, and TOMOYO Linux lets each process declare behaviors and resources needed to achieve their purpose (like an immigration officer). When configured to restrict access, TOMOYO Linux restricts each process to only these declared behaviors and resources (like an operation watchdog). This approach makes it possible for users to understand how a Linux system works. You can use TOMOYO Linux as a system analysis tool as well as an access restriction tool.</td></tr>
</table>

<h2>Introduction to this guide</h2>

<p>This guide aims to provide an informative set of instructions on how to use TOMOYO Linux, while also remaining as concise and easy to follow as possible. The guide has been split into a number of phases, which are outlined below. For those using this project for system analysis, phases 1 to 4 are relevant. For those using this project for system restriction, the six phases should provide a solid foundation from which a policy of least privilege can be developed for any particular system. The Mandatory Access Control (MAC) provided by this project is not designed to offer protection "out of the box", but instead requires time and an understanding of the concepts and tools involved. It is therefore extremely worthwhile to read this guide and develop a thorough understanding in order to make your system as secure as possible.</p>

